<DOC><DOCNO> AP890702-0010 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-02-89 1126EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Philippines     07-02 0236</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Philippines,0241</SECOND><HEAD>Eight Rebels Killed in Clash Near U.S. Base</HEAD><DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Government troops clashed withcommunist guerrillas in a village near the U.S.-run Clark Air Base,and eight rebels and a government soldier were killed, the militaryreported Sunday.   Four soldiers were wounded in the battle Saturday near AngelesCity, 50 miles northwest of Manila, a report from the PhilippineConstabulary headquarters in Manila said.   Troops recovered six M-16 rifles and rebel documents from theslain New People's Army guerrillas, the report said.   The rebels were surrounded at a house in Duquit village, about amile from the air base. The house had been under surveillance forsome time, said a constabulary soldier who requested anonymity. Thesoldier was contacted by telephone from Angeles City, home of ClarkAir Base.   He said the rebels fired first and troops retaliated afterordering civilians out of the house. He quoted officials as sayingthe rebels could have been preparing for operations in the city tocoincide with July 4 celebrations. July 4 also is celebrated in thePhilippines as Fil-American Friendship Day.   The New People's Army has been fighting 20 years to set up aMarxist system in the Philippines. It also wants the removal of U.S.military facilities from the Philippines.   In October 1987, rebels killed three Americans and a Filipino ofU.S. descent during a series of ambushes outside Clark Air Base.</TEXT></DOC>